  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When selling property in Queensland, you are required by law to have a solicitor or licensed conveyancer handle the legal transfer of ownership. This is not optional, and it applies regardless of whether you are selling through an agent or privately. The contract, the discharge of any mortgage, the transfer of title, and the settlement process all require professional handling that you cannot lawfully do yourself.</p>

      <p>What many sellers are less clear on is what their solicitor or conveyancer actually does during a sale, when to engage them, and what they will charge. Those are the questions worth understanding before your campaign begins.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a solicitor or conveyancer does when you sell</h2>
      <p>On the seller's side, the work starts with preparing or reviewing the contract of sale. In Queensland, the seller is responsible for providing the contract, and it needs to be compliant with the Property Law Act 1974 and include certain mandatory disclosures. Your legal representative prepares or checks this document before it goes to buyers.</p>

      <p>Once a buyer signs and the contract becomes unconditional, your solicitor or conveyancer coordinates with your lender to discharge any mortgage secured against the property, liaises with the buyer's legal representative to prepare for settlement, and handles the transfer of title documents through the Queensland Titles Registry. On settlement day, they facilitate the actual transfer of funds and confirm that ownership has been legally transferred to the buyer.</p>

      <p>If complications arise during the contract period, such as a buyer requesting an extension, a dispute about inclusions, or issues raised during the building and pest inspection, your legal representative advises you on how to respond and manages the written communication required under the contract.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Solicitor versus conveyancer: what is the difference</h2>
      <p>A solicitor is a fully qualified lawyer who can advise on property law and also on related matters such as tax implications, estate planning, or any legal complexity that arises during or after the sale. A licensed conveyancer specialises specifically in property transfers and can handle the vast majority of residential sales competently, but cannot provide broader legal advice if issues fall outside standard conveyancing.</p>

      <p>For a straightforward residential sale, a licensed conveyancer is often sufficient and may charge a lower fee than a solicitor. For more complex situations, such as sales involving deceased estates, trust ownership, development lots, or properties with unresolved legal issues, a solicitor is generally the safer choice because they have the scope to advise on connected legal matters.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What it costs</h2>
      <p>Legal fees for selling a residential property in Queensland vary by provider and the complexity of the transaction. As a general guide, conveyancing fees for a standard residential sale typically fall in the range of $1,200 to $2,200 in professional fees, plus disbursements. Disbursements are out-of-pocket costs that your representative pays on your behalf, such as title search fees, PEXA fees for electronic settlement, and land registry charges.</p>

      <p>Some providers quote an all-inclusive fixed fee covering both professional fees and standard disbursements, which makes it easier to budget. Others quote the professional fee separately and itemise disbursements at the end. It is worth clarifying which approach applies when you engage someone, and asking for a written cost estimate upfront.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When to engage your solicitor or conveyancer</h2>
      <p>The right time to engage your legal representative is before your property goes to market, not after you receive an offer. There are two reasons for this. First, the seller is responsible for providing the contract to prospective buyers in Queensland, and your agent will need a draft contract before they begin marketing. Second, if a buyer wants to move quickly and signs a contract, you need your legal representative already briefed and ready to act.</p>

      <p>In practice, many sellers engage their solicitor or conveyancer at the same time as they sign their agency agreement. Your agent should be able to refer you to providers they have worked with, though you are not obligated to use anyone they recommend and it is worth getting more than one quote.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens without one</h2>
      <p>You cannot legally complete a property sale in Queensland without qualified legal representation handling the settlement and title transfer. Attempting to do so would expose you to serious legal and financial risk, and would almost certainly fail at the settlement stage when the titles registry and any lenders involved require properly prepared documentation. This is not an area where cost-cutting is practical or legal.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Choosing who to use</h2>
      <p>Look for a provider who handles Queensland residential conveyancing regularly and can give you a clear written fee estimate upfront. Response time matters during a sale, particularly in the days around settlement, so ask about their process for staying in contact with you during the contract period. A good conveyancer or solicitor will keep you informed at each stage without you having to chase them for updates.</p>

      <p>Your real estate agent can usually recommend several providers they have worked with and trust. These referrals are worth considering because your agent and your legal representative need to communicate efficiently during the sale, and an established working relationship often helps things run more smoothly.</p>

